Therefore, we recommended the City Accountant the following:
• Make necessary information of the PPEs not provided with depreciation if complete data has been gathered; 
• Check the accuracy of information entered in the accounting system and make sure all data of the PPEs are provided; 
• Recompute the depreciation once entered into the system to verify and establish the correct amount; 
• Adjust the understatement of Accumulated Depreciation in previous years to be able to present the PPE at its proper valuation. 
• Coordinate with the system provider of the accounting system used by the Accounting Office to correct the computation of the provision for depreciation

Therefore, we recommended the following:
• Conduct disposal of the remaining unserviceable properties in accordance with the guidelines set in the HSPMS. If budget permits, provide additional staff to give attention on the inventory and disposal of unserviceable properties;
• Submit the necessary documents to the Office of the City Accountant, after the disposal, as basis of the latter in dropping the PPEs in the books of accounts;
• Continue reconciling with the record of the City Accountant with regard to the already disposed PPEs for proper dropping in the books;
• After the disposal, the City Accountant to draw journal entry vouchers to derecognize the properties and apply appropriate accounting procedures to effect adjustments in the books. Also, make extra effort in reconciling PPEs already disposed but were not yet dropped in the books of accounts.

Therefore, we recommended the following:
For the City Accountant to:
• Review and investigate the remaining CIP accounts and transfer all completed PPAs to completed PPE accounts in consideration with the certificate of completion submitted by the City Engineering Office;
• Provide depreciation to those assets not yet fully depreciated for proper presentation in the Financial Statements;
• Reconcile records with the accomplishment report of the CPDO monitoring team and investigate variances for proper adjustment/s in the books;
• Retrieve the documents related to the completed and on-going PPAs amounting to ₱6,680,000.00 and make the necessary adjustment/s in the books.
For the City Planning and Development Officer to:
• Require the monitoring team under CPDO to reconcile accomplishment report with the accounting records as well as the Budget Office and CEO to ensure completeness and accurateness of the monitoring report and investigate variances;
For the City Engineering Office to:
• Prepare the Certificate of Completion supported with the project inspection report for PPAs implemented "by administration" upon completion and constantly submit the same to the Accounting Office for proper recording;
• Request for additional personnel with technical expertise so that monitoring of PPAs and submission of reports will be timely done.

Therefore, we recommended the following measures to be carried out by the City Accountant to present fairly the Cash in Bank-LCCA account in the Financial Statements:
• Locate and trace down the documents to support the adjusting entries on the long outstanding reconciling items and investigate reconciling items; 
• Coordinate, reconcile and investigate the book errors; 
• Request copies from the bank of the debit memos and credit memos issued for proper recording in the books of accounts; 
• Record adjustments for valid reconciling items per books as reflected in the BRS prepared; 
• Coordinate with the bank personnel relative to the identified bank errors and make a representation to make the necessary adjustments; 
• For the City Treasurer, in coordination with the other officials, to enroll the accounts of the City on the available online platforms of the AGDBs (e.g., We Access of LBP) to automatically check transaction history of the accounts which could be used to prepare the BRS.

Therefore, we recommended the following:
For the Bids and Awards Committee (BAC) Chairman to:
- Hire additional staff and assign them as canvassers per project and type basis so that huge number of procurements will be timely addressed;
- Instruct the canvassers to prepare on time the POs and other necessary documents and submit immediately the documents to the General Service Office upon confirmation by the supplier/contractor;
- Review the POs especially the data provided on the delivery term and assess if it is possible for the supplier to deliver the materials on the provided timeframe.
We also recommended the City Accountant to intensify the review of the completeness of supporting documents more particularly those pertaining to DVs on procurement, such as, but not limited to the receipted copy of the notice to losing bidder.
For the City General Service Officer:
- Impose liquidated damages for late deliveries of supplies and materials pursuant to aforestated provision of the 2016 revised IRR of RA No. 9184 to prevent suppliers from neglecting their responsibility to comply the conditions of the contract and to avoid delay in the implementation of the projects;
- Follow up to the concerned department the proposed construction of warehouse of the City;
- Impose appropriate measures.

Therefore, we recommended that the CDRRMO, in coordination with the CDRRMC, to:
• Stop the practice of continuing the MOOE PPAs proposed against the previous years STF and subject the same to another/or the same PPAs, if needed, at the beginning of the ensuing year or during the budget preparation, as the case may be;
• Review and update the LDRRMFIP annually, incorporating therein any unutilized fund from the previously enacted utilization of STF, excluding capital outlay.

Therefore, we recommended the following:
For the Local Finance Committee to:
• Prepare the Report on Fund Utilization and Status of Programs/ Projects/ Activities Implementation in a monthly basis;
• Post the accumulated reports on the LGU’s website and in at least three (3) conspicuous places in the locality at the end of every month;
For the Local Chief Executive to:
• Send a written notice to the DBM, House of Representatives, Senate of the Philippines, House of Committee on Appropriations, Senate Committee on Finance, and other offices where the submission of reports is required under existing laws, rules and regulations, when said reports have been posted on its website.

Therefore, we recommended the following:
• Make the necessary adjusting entries to record the “Due to Other Funds” account to close the erroneous financial assistance disbursed out of the BGCM; 
• Stop the charging of administrative expenses against the BGCM; 
• Ensure that disbursements will conform to the rules and regulations of the utilization of BGCM;
• Review and ensure that expenses are correctly obligated to proper funds based on approved annual/ supplemental budgets.

Therefore, we recommended the following:
For all Department Heads and concerned City Personnel to:
• Require the submission of the duly filled-up driver’s trip tickets every time the motor vehicle is used for official travels to support the reasonableness of the refilling of tanks;
• Strictly enforce complete and proper accomplishment of driver’s trip ticket;
• Stop the practice of refueling private vehicles and filling up tanks out of the government sources, instead, concerned personnel can claim equivalent fare when using private vehicles for official travels;
• Strengthen controls in the withdrawal of fuel to ensure expenditures are not excessive and unnecessary; 
• Require the preparation and submission of the Monthly Report of Official Travels (Annex N) as well as the Monthly Report of Fuel Consumption (Annex O);
For the City Accountant to:
• Record fuels, oils and lubricants used for the repairs and maintenance of road networks under Repairs and Maintenance – Infrastructure Assets account, or applicable accounts;
For the City Budget Officer to:
• Incorporate the budget for repair and maintenance under the Repair and Maintenance budget line and not under Fuel, Oil and Lubricants in the ensuing year;
For the City Engineer to:
• Prepare program of work for all the regular repair and maintenance of infrastructure assets of the City to indicate the budget needs of the project which could be used as part of the supporting documents in the proper recording of the transaction and controls in the expenses charged.

Therefore, we recommended for the City Planning and Development Coordinator to:
• Formulate/ develop specific strategies/ solutions to effectively implement the projects and prioritize what should be accomplished without sacrificing the quality of work; 
• Look into the unimplemented development projects under the 20% Development Fund and determine causes of non-implementation; 
• Reprogram to other priority projects, if necessary, that will conform to the present condition of the City and formulate a timetable that will determine the exact period when the project will be implemented as well as monitor the status of its implementation; 
• Before approval of the project, review the availability of technical personnel and feasibility of implementing the projects within a realistic timeline in identifying PPAs to be funded by the 20% DF.
For the Concerned Implementing Office: 
• Coordinate with the City Engineering office and ensure that program of works, project designs, detailed estimates, coordination with other agencies and other needed documents needing approval had been prepared and approved without objections prior to its inclusion to the Annual Investment Plan; 
• Fast track the implementation based on the scheduled time frames indicated in the AIP to achieve the desired management outcomes.

Therefore, we recommended for the CDRRMO to do the following:
• Conduct regular monitoring activities with the program holders to check the status of the PPAs to avoid/minimize disaster projected and for preparedness and response capabilities; 
• Review regularly the viability of the PPAs in the LDRRMFIP and as practicable, PPAs which are no longer needed to be recommended for reprogramming; 
• Recommend to the Local Chief Executive to augment manpower needs of the BAC Secretariat to fast track procurement process.

Therefore, we recommended that the City Accountant will do the following to present fairly the receivable accounts of the City in the Financial Statements:
• Send demand letters to officials and employees who are no longer connected with the City but whose whereabouts are still known to liquidate their cash advances/receivables and consider taking legal actions/remedies against them;
• Gather all documents that will prove that liquidation/payment of the named individuals is no longer possible such as those who are deceased and request for write-off upon verification;
• Make a report on negative balances of accounts of accountable officers and payback what has been over collected, if applicable upon conduct of review on the accounts;
• Develop internal control procedure to ensure proper monitoring of loan payments granted to organized groups or individuals and guarantee collectability of the same.

Therefore, we recommended that the City Accountant will do the following:
• Confirm the amount of the payables from the list of the identified creditors to determine which of the payables are still valid and to make necessary adjustments in the books;
• Adjust the payable accounts if proven to be undocumented and without existing claimants especially those accounts which are outstanding for more than 2 years as stated in Section 98 of PD 1445;
• Review the validity of accounts payable in a regular basis to promptly determine which of the accounts are already dormant and to take necessary remedial measures;
• Review and investigate the negative balances and make necessary demand on the payables of the management against the concerned supplier/creditor/employee, if applicable; and
• Make the necessary adjustments in the books should review and investigation of the negative balances were due to erroneous recording.

Therefore, we recommended that the City Accountant to:
• Exert effort to reconstruct the list of PPE accounts which are for reconciliation and coordinate closely with other Departments for proper substantiation of accounts;
• Transfer completed PPEs of Trust Fund to the General Fund and subject the same to depreciation;
• Review and verify the Accumulated depreciation which are non-moving and provide the necessary depreciation expense.
For the City General Services Officer to:
• Ensure that properties physically counted were recorded in the same PPE accounts with the Accounting Office to facilitate reconciliation;
• Reconcile records with the Accounting Office so that PPE-Land Account is presented fairly in the financial statement.
For the City Mayor to:
• Augment manpower needs of the CGSO, if budget permits.

Therefore, we recommended that the City Accountant to:
• Transfer all completed CIP accounts to proper PPE accounts in consideration of Certificate of Completion submitted by CEO;
• Retrieve the documents related to the completed and on-going PPAs and make necessary adjustments in the books;
• Reconcile records with CPDO and CEO and adjust accordingly.
For the City Planning and Development Officer to:
• Require monitoring team under CPDO to reconcile monitoring reports with accounting and Budget Office and CEO;
For the City Engineering Office to:
• Retrieve/prepare supporting documents and certifications of completion and submit to Accounting Office for proper posting; 
• Request additional personnel with technical expertise to handle monitoring and documentation.

Therefore, we recommended that the City Planning and Development Coordinator to:
• Closely monitor utilization and implementation of priority projects for the attainment of socio-economic development and maximize the usage of the fund;
• Recommend to the Local Development Council to reprogram the savings out of the completed projects (both from continuing and current appropriation);
For the Concerned Implementing Office:
• Coordinate with CEO to ensure program of works, project designs and documents prepared prior to inclusion in AIP; 
• Fast track the implementation based on scheduled time frames indicated in the AIP.

Therefore, we recommended that the CDRRMO in coordination with LDRRMC to:
• Revisit PPAs in the LDIP if such were still feasible to address current development in the City and revise the same, if need be, in accordance to the long-term objectives of the LGU;
• Harmonize local planning, investment programming, revenue administration, budgeting, and expenditure management prescribed in the DBM-NEDA-DILG-DOF Joint Memorandum Circular No. 1, series of 2007 dated March 8, 2007.

1. Instruct the CEOED to evaluate the existing LEEs using the manual provided by the DBM in the setting up and operations of LEEs and make appropriate actions based on the evaluation whether to continue or discontinue the LEEs;
2. Revisit Local Budget Circular No. 111 for a more effective management of local economic enterprises;
3. Revisit and strictly comply with the provisions of Local Budget Circular No. 100 dated October 1, 2012 especially on the operation of Cemetery and Market; 
4. Revisit and strictly comply with the provisions of Local Budget Circular No. 111 dated October 1, 2012 particularly on the setting up and operation of Local Economic Enterprises; 
For specific LEEs, provide actions such as codification of rates, completion of building works, and other measures to ensure financial viability.

Therefore, we recommended the following:
• Send demand letters to officials and employees who are no longer connected with the City but whose whereabouts are still known to liquidate their obligations and consider legal remedies; 
• Gather documents to prove liquidation/payment for those who are deceased or whose liquidation is no longer possible and request write-off where appropriate in accordance with COA Circular 2016-005; 
• Make a report on negative balances of accounts of accountable officers and recover over-collections if applicable;
• Develop internal control to monitor loan repayments and ensure collectability.

Therefore, we recommended that the City Accountant to:
• Locate and trace down the documents to cast the documents to support the adjusting entries on the long outstanding reconciling items
• Coordinate, reconcile and investigate the book errors;
• Request copies from the bank of the debit memos and credit memos issued for proper recording in the books of accounts;
• Record adjustments for valid reconciling items per books as of long outstanding reflected in the BRS prepared;
• Coordinate with the bank personnel relative to the identified bank errors and make a representation to make the necessary adjustments;
• Locate the stale checks if it is still with the City Treasurer and make the necessary adjustments. If the check is not available, confirm the payable account with the payee and make the proper procedures for replacing the check. If no response was received, make the necessary adjustments with the books.

